Day 4 — Networking Fundamentals (OSI & TCP/IP Models)

OSI Model (7 Layers)
Physical → Data Link → Network → Transport → Session → Presentation → Application. Each layer handles a specific function in how data moves across a network, 
from raw bits up to user-facing applications.

TCP/IP Model (4 Layers)
Network Access → Internet → Transport → Application — the practical, simplified model the internet actually runs on, mapping roughly onto OSI's seven layers.

Networking Devices
Routers (connect networks, route traffic), Switches (connect devices within a LAN), Firewalls (filter traffic based on rules), Hubs (broadcast to all ports), 
Access Points (wireless connectivity).

Key Protocols
TCP/UDP (transport), HTTP/HTTPS (web traffic), DNS (domain resolution), DHCP (IP assignment), FTP/SFTP (file transfer), SMTP (email).

Why It Matters for SOC Work
Understanding these layers and protocols is essential for reading packet captures, spotting anomalous traffic, and knowing where in the stack an attack or failure is occurring.
